The Council on Higher Education's report, found many universities don't equip their law students with sufficient critical thinking skills. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - A new report highlights a range of shortcomings in the Bachelor of Laws programme taught at 17 universities in the country. The Council on Higher Education's (CHE) report, found many universities don't equip their law students with sufficient critical thinking skills. READ: Education sector shake up needed "Indeed the findings were that there were shortcomings and these shortcomings were referred back to the universities...together in a partnership between the CHE and the universities", said Universities South Africa CEO, Professor Ahmed Bawa. The Higher Education committee recommends extensive changes to LLB tuition. "All 17 universities have now gone through the process and the legal programs are kind of back on track", he said. 